and to the limits of cultural nationalism as promoted by a one-party state.Through an engrossing analysis of music and film, as well as fanzines, newspapers, government documents, company reports, and numerous interviews, Zolov shows how rock music culture became a volatile commodity force, whose production and consumption strategies were shaped by intellectuals, state agencies, transnational and local capital, musicians, and fans alike. More than a history of Mexican rock and roll, Zolov's study demonstrates the politicized nature of culture under authoritarianism, and offers a nuanced discussion of the effects of cultural imperialism that deepens our understanding of gender relations, social hierarchies, and the very meanings of national identity in a transnational era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMusicxSocial aspectszMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and culturezMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aRock musiczMexicoxHistory and criticism. 0aSocial valueszMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aYouth movementszMexicozMexico CityxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a1950s.  a1960s.  a1970s.  aacademic.  aamerican music.  aauthoritarianism.  acinema studies.  acounterculture.  acultural studies.  aculture.  aelvis presley.  aelvis.  afilm studies.  aimperialism.  ainterviews.  amexican culture.  amexican politics.  amexican society.  amodern world.  amodernization.  amusic culture.  amusic genre.  amusic history.  anational identity.  anationalism.  apatriarchal.  apatriarchy.  apolitical.  arebellion.  aregional.  aresearch.  arock and roll.  arock music.  ascholarly.  asocial hierarchies.  asocial studies.  atransnational.  atrue story.  awe